WEBVTT

1
00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:14.960
You ready?

2
00:01:15.160 --> 00:01:18.000
No, just... Yeah, just... just
ignore the microphone.

3
00:01:18.320 --> 00:01:20.240
Yeah, just... just act
as if it's not there.

4
00:01:20.320 --> 00:01:23.000
Sing as if it's not there.

5
00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:24.080
Yeah...

6
00:01:24.160 --> 00:01:30.040
(German)

7
00:01:31.360 --> 00:01:33.800
(German)

8
00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:35.440
Okay?

9
00:05:29.080 --> 00:05:30.160
Ready for them?

10
00:05:30.240 --> 00:05:31.800
- Yes.
- Let's go.

11
00:05:39.280 --> 00:05:42.240
If you're here,
then you already know who she is

12
00:05:42.320 --> 00:05:45.720
and that is one of the most important
musical figures of our time.

13
00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:48.320
Lydia Tár is many things:

14
00:05:48.400 --> 00:05:51.480
a piano performance graduate
at the Curtis Institute

15
00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:53.960
Phi Beta Kappa from Harvard.

16
00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:58.000
She got her PhD in Musicology
from the University of Vienna

17
00:05:58.080 --> 00:06:00.360
specializing in the indigenous music

18
00:06:00.440 --> 00:06:03.080
of the Ucayali Valley in Eastern Peru

19
00:06:03.160 --> 00:06:06.760
where she spent five years
among the Shipibo-Konibo people.

20
00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:11.560
As a conductor, Tár began her career
with the Cleveland Orchestra

21
00:06:11.640 --> 00:06:13.400
one of the so-called "Big Five."

22
00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:17.680
A string of important posts followed,
including the Philadelphia Orchestra

23
00:06:17.760 --> 00:06:19.440
the Chicago Symphony Orchestra

24
00:06:19.520 --> 00:06:21.080
the Boston Symphony Orchestra

25
00:06:21.160 --> 00:06:24.880
until she at last arrived here
at our own New York Philharmonic.

26
00:06:24.960 --> 00:06:28.600
With the latter, she organized
the Highway 10 refugee concerts

27
00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:29.720
in Zaatari

28
00:06:29.800 --> 00:06:33.240
which were attended
by over 75,000 people.

29
00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:37.360
She's become particularly well-known
for commissioning contemporary work

30
00:06:37.440 --> 00:06:40.320
from, among others,
Jennifer Higdon, Caroline Shaw

31
00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:42.600
Julia Wolfe and Hildur Gudnadóttir.

32
00:06:42.920 --> 00:06:45.400
And she's made a point
of programming their works

33
00:06:45.480 --> 00:06:48.080
alongside composers of the canon.

34
00:06:48.520 --> 00:06:50.080
She's been quoted as saying

35
00:06:50.160 --> 00:06:52.600
"These composers
are having a conversation

36
00:06:52.680 --> 00:06:54.920
and it may not always be so polite."

37
00:06:55.480 --> 00:06:58.400
Lydia Tár has also written music
for the stage and screen.

38
00:06:58.480 --> 00:07:02.400
She is in fact
one of only 15 so-called EGOTs

39
00:07:02.480 --> 00:07:06.520
meaning those who have won
all four major entertainment awards:

40
00:07:06.600 --> 00:07:10.320
an Emmy, a Grammy,
an Oscar and a Tony.

41
00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:11.880
It is, as you can imagine

42
00:07:11.960 --> 00:07:14.360
an extremely short
and shimmering list

43
00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:17.400
that includes Richard Rodgers,
Audrey Hepburn

44
00:07:17.480 --> 00:07:20.680
Andrew Lloyd Webber
and, of course, Mel Brooks.

45
00:07:24.720 --> 00:07:27.600
In 2010, with the support
of Eliot Kaplan

46
00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:30.560
she founded
the Accordion Conducting Fellowship

47
00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:33.800
which fosters entrepreneurship
and performance opportunities

48
00:07:33.880 --> 00:07:35.600
for female conductors

49
00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:39.120
allowing them residencies with
major orchestras around the world.

50
00:07:39.720 --> 00:07:44.640
In 2013, Berlin elected Tár
as its principal conductor

51
00:07:44.720 --> 00:07:47.000
in succession to Andris Davis

52
00:07:47.080 --> 00:07:49.200
and she's remained there ever since.

53
00:07:49.880 --> 00:07:51.840
Like her mentor, Leonard Bernstein

54
00:07:51.920 --> 00:07:54.680
Tár has a particular affinity
for Mahler

55
00:07:54.760 --> 00:07:58.520
whose nine symphonies she recorded
during her Big Five stints.

56
00:07:59.240 --> 00:08:01.000
However, she never
managed to complete

57
00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:04.760
the so-called "cycle" with
a single orchestra until now.

58
00:08:04.840 --> 00:08:06.520
Under her direction,
Berlin has recorded

59
00:08:06.600 --> 00:08:08.200
eight of the Mahler symphonies

60
00:08:08.280 --> 00:08:10.880
saving the big one,
<i>Symphony No. 5</i>, for last.

61
00:08:10.960 --> 00:08:12.200
Due to the pandemic

62
00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:14.600
that performance
which was scheduled for last year

63
00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:15.680
had to be canceled.

64
00:08:15.760 --> 00:08:17.280
But I'm told that next month

65
00:08:17.360 --> 00:08:19.720
she'll make a live recording
of Mahler's Fifth

66
00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:21.560
which will complete the cycle

67
00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:25.120
and will be issued in a box set
by Deutsche Grammophon

68
00:08:25.200 --> 00:08:27.240
just in time for Mahler's birthday.

69
00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:31.040
As if that's not enough,
her new book, <i>Tár on Tár</i>

70
00:08:31.120 --> 00:08:34.560
will be published
by Nan Talese's imprint at Doubleday

71
00:08:34.640 --> 00:08:37.840
just in time for Christmas,
a perfect stocking stuffer

72
00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:40.200
especially if you have
a very large stocking.

73
00:08:41.440 --> 00:08:42.856
All of us at <i>The New Yorker</i>
welcome you.

74
00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:44.280
Thank you for joining us, Maestro

75
00:08:44.360 --> 00:08:46.000
- today.
- Thank you, Adam. Thank you.

76
00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:48.520
Thank you.

77
00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:51.600
Lydia, I couldn't...

78
00:08:52.080 --> 00:08:54.920
I couldn't help
but see you flinch just a little bit

79
00:08:55.000 --> 00:08:56.040
as I was reading your bio.

80
00:08:56.080 --> 00:08:58.920
Was it because I forgot
some other amazing achievement?

81
00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:01.200
Or do you have
a slight self-consciousness

82
00:09:01.280 --> 00:09:04.400
about the incredibly varied things
that you've accomplished?

83
00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:10.080
Well, in today's world,
"varied," it... it's a dirty word.

84
00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:12.120
I mean, our era is one of specialists

85
00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:15.000
and if you're trying to do
more than one thing

86
00:09:15.080 --> 00:09:16.760
it's, you know,
it's often frowned upon.

87
00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:18.000
Every artist gets typecast.

88
00:09:18.120 --> 00:09:19.800
Oh, yes. Aggressively so.

89
00:09:19.880 --> 00:09:21.456
Well, do you think
there'll be a moment, though

90
00:09:21.480 --> 00:09:23.400
when the classical music community

91
00:09:23.480 --> 00:09:26.840
decides not to use
sexual distinctions

92
00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:28.440
to differentiate artists?

93
00:09:28.840 --> 00:09:33.240
I'm probably the wrong person to ask
since I don't read reviews.

94
00:09:33.320 --> 00:09:34.640
- Never, really?
- No.

95
00:09:34.720 --> 00:09:39.000
But it is odd, I... I think,
that anyone ever felt compelled

96
00:09:39.080 --> 00:09:41.640
to substitute "maestro"
with "maestra."

97
00:09:41.720 --> 00:09:45.360
I mean, we don't call
women astronauts "astronettes."

98
00:09:45.440 --> 00:09:46.440
Right.

99
00:09:46.520 --> 00:09:50.000
But as to the question of gender bias

100
00:09:50.360 --> 00:09:52.680
I really have nothing
to complain about.

101
00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:55.720
Nor, for that matter, should
Marin Alsop, JoAnn Falletta

102
00:09:55.960 --> 00:09:57.920
Laurence Equilbey
and Nathalie Stutzmann.

103
00:09:58.000 --> 00:10:01.840
I mean, there's so many
incredible women who came before us.

104
00:10:01.920 --> 00:10:04.280
You know, women who did
the... the real lifting.

105
00:10:04.360 --> 00:10:06.920
That... that's fascinating.
Can you... Who, for instance?

106
00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:08.680
Okay, sure.

107
00:10:08.760 --> 00:10:10.880
First and foremost, Nadia Boulanger.

108
00:10:10.960 --> 00:10:13.640
I mean, that would be
the... happy example.

109
00:10:13.720 --> 00:10:16.840
The sad one would be Antonia Brico

110
00:10:16.920 --> 00:10:19.680
who by all accounts
was an incredible conductor

111
00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:21.000
but was ghettoized

112
00:10:21.080 --> 00:10:24.520
into the non-glamorous status
of a "guest conductor"

113
00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:27.520
and essentially treated as a dog act.

114
00:10:27.600 --> 00:10:30.800
A dog... She never got the chance
to lead a major orchestra?

115
00:10:30.880 --> 00:10:32.640
Well, yes. Yes, she did conduct

116
00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:34.920
the Berlin Philharmonic,
as well as the Met

117
00:10:35.040 --> 00:10:37.640
but, again,
only as a guest conductor.

118
00:10:38.240 --> 00:10:39.896
You know, at, I mean,
at that time it was...

119
00:10:39.920 --> 00:10:42.000
it was all gender spectacle.

120
00:10:42.080 --> 00:10:43.480
But fortunately, times change

121
00:10:43.560 --> 00:10:45.840
and... and the Pauline
conversion is...

122
00:10:45.920 --> 00:10:46.976
- "Pauline..."
- if not complete

123
00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:48.720
then it's... it's evolving nicely.

124
00:10:48.800 --> 00:10:51.400
N-No less
having fallen off its horse.

125
00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:55.160
Lydia, could we talk a little bit
about translation?

126
00:10:55.400 --> 00:10:56.656
'Cause I think there's still people

127
00:10:56.680 --> 00:10:59.640
who think of the conductor
as a kind of human metronome.

128
00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:03.960
Well, yeah,
that's... that's partly true.

129
00:11:04.040 --> 00:11:05.800
- Yeah, but it's...
- But keeping time

130
00:11:05.880 --> 00:11:07.760
it's... it's no small thing.

131
00:11:07.840 --> 00:11:09.256
But I suspect
there's a lot more to it than that.

132
00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:10.736
Yeah, well,
I... I would hope so, yes.

133
00:11:10.760 --> 00:11:13.200
But time is the thing.

134
00:11:13.600 --> 00:11:17.760
Time is... is the essential piece
of interpretation.

135
00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:19.440
You cannot start without me.

136
00:11:19.520 --> 00:11:21.280
See, I start the clock.

137
00:11:21.560 --> 00:11:25.760
Now, my left hand shapes,
but my right hand, the second hand

138
00:11:25.840 --> 00:11:28.720
marks time and moves it forward.

139
00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:32.400
However, unlike a clock,
sometimes my second hand stops

140
00:11:32.680 --> 00:11:35.760
which means that time stops.

141
00:11:35.840 --> 00:11:40.440
Now, the illusion is that like you,
I'm responding to the orchestra

142
00:11:40.520 --> 00:11:42.056
- in real time, making the decision
- Right, right.

143
00:11:42.080 --> 00:11:44.400
About the right moment
to restart the thing, or reset it

144
00:11:44.480 --> 00:11:47.120
or throw time out
the window altogether.

145
00:11:47.200 --> 00:11:50.200
The reality is that
right from the very beginning

146
00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:52.600
- I know precisely what time it is
- Really?

147
00:11:52.680 --> 00:11:53.840
And the exact moment

148
00:11:53.920 --> 00:11:56.880
that you and I will arrive
at our destination together.

149
00:11:57.240 --> 00:12:01.880
You know, the only real discovery
for me is in rehearsal.

150
00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:04.000
It's never, never in performance.

151
00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:05.640
Hard question, I know

152
00:12:05.720 --> 00:12:09.240
but if you could define one thing
that Bernstein gave you

153
00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:10.360
what would it be?

154
00:12:12.520 --> 00:12:13.520
Kavvanah.

155
00:12:13.880 --> 00:12:15.280
Yeah, it's... it's the Hebrew word

156
00:12:15.360 --> 00:12:18.000
for attention to meaning
or... or intent.

157
00:12:18.080 --> 00:12:19.656
You know, what are
the composer's priorities

158
00:12:19.680 --> 00:12:22.000
and what are yours, and how do
they complement one another?

159
00:12:22.080 --> 00:12:24.160
Right, kavvanah. I think
that's a word that will have

160
00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:26.320
a slightly different meaning
for many in our audience.

161
00:12:26.400 --> 00:12:28.600
Well, yes, yes, I imagine so.

162
00:12:29.120 --> 00:12:30.176
Am I right in thinking that

163
00:12:30.200 --> 00:12:33.600
a conductor was not always
an onstage presence

164
00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:34.736
- in classical music?
- No, that's right.

165
00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:35.920
I... I think I read someplace

166
00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.640
that it actually was
the first violin, for a long time

167
00:12:38.720 --> 00:12:39.816
- who was responsible.
- Yes, the first violinist

168
00:12:39.840 --> 00:12:42.800
whether they had any interest
or... or skill in it or not.

169
00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:45.200
W-when did that change,
and... and who changed it?

170
00:12:45.720 --> 00:12:48.920
With the French composer,
Jean-Baptiste Lully

171
00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:54.360
who reportedly used
a rather enormous rather pointy staff

172
00:12:54.440 --> 00:12:56.440
to pound the tempi into the floor.

173
00:12:56.520 --> 00:13:00.000
It's not something I imagine
the players particularly appreciated.

174
00:13:00.080 --> 00:13:03.600
Anyway, that technique ended
during a performance

175
00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:05.760
when Lully accidentally

176
00:13:05.840 --> 00:13:07.880
stabbed himself in the foot
with the thing and died.

177
00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:09.960
Yeah, of... of gangrene.

178
00:13:11.040 --> 00:13:12.040
But anyway...

179
00:13:13.680 --> 00:13:14.680
Yeah.

180
00:13:14.920 --> 00:13:18.280
Anyway, but the conductor

181
00:13:18.400 --> 00:13:22.000
really becomes essential
as the ensembles get bigger.

182
00:13:22.080 --> 00:13:24.560
And once again,
we go back to Beethoven.

183
00:13:27.280 --> 00:13:29.440
Now, that doesn't start
with the eighth note.

184
00:13:29.520 --> 00:13:30.720
The downbeat...

185
00:13:31.760 --> 00:13:33.440
it's silent, right?

186
00:13:33.520 --> 00:13:35.720
So someone had to start that clock.

187
00:13:36.080 --> 00:13:38.880
Someone had to plant
their flag in the sand

188
00:13:38.960 --> 00:13:41.400
and say, "Follow me," you know?

189
00:13:41.480 --> 00:13:44.720
And when that someone was Lenny,
the orchestra was led

190
00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:48.800
on the most extraordinary
tour of pleasures.

191
00:13:48.880 --> 00:13:51.720
'Cause he knew the music,
Mahler especially

192
00:13:51.800 --> 00:13:53.840
as well or better than anyone.

193
00:13:53.920 --> 00:13:56.680
And he would often play
with the form.

194
00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:58.176
'Cause he wanted an orchestra to feel

195
00:13:58.200 --> 00:14:00.640
that they had never seen,
let alone heard

196
00:14:00.720 --> 00:14:03.200
or... or performed any of that music.

197
00:14:03.280 --> 00:14:05.320
So he... he would do radical things

198
00:14:05.400 --> 00:14:07.600
like disregarding the tempo primo

199
00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:10.160
or... or ending this phrase
molto ritardando

200
00:14:10.240 --> 00:14:12.200
even though it had no such marking.

201
00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:13.560
Was he over-egging it?

202
00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:15.000
Oh, no, no, no. Not at all.

203
00:14:15.080 --> 00:14:18.600
He... he celebrated
the joy of his discovery.

204
00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:20.520
You told us a moment ago

205
00:14:20.600 --> 00:14:23.000
that your discovery
takes place in rehearsal.

206
00:14:23.080 --> 00:14:24.800
When will that process
begin again for you?

207
00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:27.240
We start on Monday.

208
00:14:27.720 --> 00:14:28.760
Immediately?

209
00:14:29.400 --> 00:14:31.760
With this one, it really is about

210
00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:35.720
trying to read the tea leaves
of... of Mahler's intention.

211
00:14:36.080 --> 00:14:39.240
I mean, we know a great deal
about this with his other symphonies.

212
00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:41.336
You know, he was so inspired
by the poetry of Rückert

213
00:14:41.360 --> 00:14:43.640
that for years he didn't set
another author to music.

214
00:14:43.720 --> 00:14:46.360
But all of this changes
with the Five.

215
00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:48.840
The Five is a mystery.

216
00:14:48.920 --> 00:14:51.560
And the only clue he leaves us

217
00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:53.400
is on the cover
of the manuscript itself.

218
00:14:53.480 --> 00:14:57.000
Yes, the... the dedication
to his new wife, Alma.

219
00:14:57.480 --> 00:15:01.520
So if you're gonna partner
with Mahler on his fifth symphony

220
00:15:02.120 --> 00:15:03.520
the first thing you must do

221
00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:08.160
is try to understand
that very complex marriage.

222
00:15:08.240 --> 00:15:09.336
And would you say that you have

223
00:15:09.360 --> 00:15:12.200
a different interpretation
of that marriage than Bernstein did?

224
00:15:14.680 --> 00:15:18.200
You mentioned my ethnographic
fieldwork in the Amazon.

225
00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:23.920
Well, Adam, the Shipibo-Konibo
only receive an icaro, or song

226
00:15:24.000 --> 00:15:25.720
if the singer is there, right?

227
00:15:25.800 --> 00:15:29.400
On the same side of the... the spirit
that... that created it.

228
00:15:29.680 --> 00:15:32.680
And in that way, the past
and the present converge.

229
00:15:32.760 --> 00:15:35.720
It's the flip sides
of the same cosmic coin.

230
00:15:36.320 --> 00:15:39.160
That definition of fidelity
makes sense to me.

231
00:15:39.240 --> 00:15:41.360
But Lenny, he believed in teshuvah.

232
00:15:41.440 --> 00:15:43.600
The... the Talmudic power
to reach back into time

233
00:15:43.680 --> 00:15:47.720
and... and transform the significance
of one's past deeds.

234
00:15:47.800 --> 00:15:51.600
So when he played the Adagietto
at Robert Kennedy's funeral

235
00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:54.200
it ran for 12 minutes.

236
00:15:54.440 --> 00:15:56.200
He treated it as a mass.

237
00:15:56.560 --> 00:15:58.520
And, you know,
if you listen to a recording of it

238
00:15:58.600 --> 00:16:02.120
you will no doubt feel
the tragedy and... and the pathos.

239
00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:06.600
And of course that interpretation was
very true for Mahler later in life

240
00:16:06.680 --> 00:16:08.520
after the professional bottom
dropped out

241
00:16:08.600 --> 00:16:10.400
and Alma had left him for Gropius.

242
00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:15.440
But, as I said before,
we are dealing with time.

243
00:16:15.520 --> 00:16:19.680
And this piece was not born
into aching tragedy.

244
00:16:19.760 --> 00:16:22.280
It was born into young love.

245
00:16:22.360 --> 00:16:23.680
And so you chose...

246
00:16:24.520 --> 00:16:25.560
Love.

247
00:16:26.600 --> 00:16:28.400
Right, but precisely how long?

248
00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:29.960
Well...

249
00:16:30.200 --> 00:16:31.320
seven minutes.

250
00:16:36.080 --> 00:16:38.880
I was so taken
by what you said to Adam

251
00:16:38.960 --> 00:16:42.160
about interpretation

252
00:16:42.400 --> 00:16:47.200
and specifically about feelings,
and that you chose love.

253
00:16:48.560 --> 00:16:49.600
And I know it's said that

254
00:16:49.680 --> 00:16:52.200
you should leave the tears
for the audience, but...

255
00:16:53.160 --> 00:16:56.040
do you ever find yourself
overwhelmed by emotion

256
00:16:56.120 --> 00:16:57.336
when you're up there at the podium?

257
00:16:57.360 --> 00:16:58.400
Yes.

258
00:16:59.080 --> 00:17:00.520
Yes, that does happen.

259
00:17:00.840 --> 00:17:04.000
There's an...
an expectation-reward cycle

260
00:17:04.080 --> 00:17:06.160
with some works and the spots in them

261
00:17:06.240 --> 00:17:09.040
that I find so incredible,
that when I'm conducting

262
00:17:09.120 --> 00:17:11.040
it's not that I'm rushing exactly

263
00:17:11.120 --> 00:17:13.600
but I just can't wait
to get to that spot

264
00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:16.200
and, yeah, it does it.
It does it every time.

265
00:17:17.640 --> 00:17:19.720
So it's physical
as well as emotional.

266
00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:23.280
God, it must take hours
to come back down to earth.

267
00:17:23.360 --> 00:17:26.520
You say things after others
remember, but you won't.

268
00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:29.000
And sleep, it's impossible.

269
00:17:29.200 --> 00:17:30.880
It's like my freshman year at Smith.

270
00:17:34.280 --> 00:17:35.680
Which piece does that to you?

271
00:17:36.160 --> 00:17:37.320
Oh, I saw you.

272
00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:40.880
I saw you conduct The Rite of Spring
at the Met last year.

273
00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:42.920
It was so powerful.

274
00:17:43.280 --> 00:17:44.280
Thank you.

275
00:17:44.520 --> 00:17:45.640
Thank you. It's...

276
00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:49.000
It's the 11 pistol shots...
it's a prime number...

277
00:17:49.080 --> 00:17:51.600
that strike you
as both victim and perpetrator.

278
00:17:51.680 --> 00:17:53.176
You know, it's not until
I conducted it

279
00:17:53.200 --> 00:17:56.640
that I became convinced
we're all capable of murder.

280
00:17:56.720 --> 00:17:59.280
That is a fantastic handbag,
by the way.

281
00:17:59.600 --> 00:18:01.360
Thank you. I'm glad you like it.

282
00:18:01.480 --> 00:18:03.320
Oh, I do. I do.

283
00:18:03.800 --> 00:18:06.760
Sorry. Your lunch with Mr. Kaplan.
His driver is waiting.

284
00:18:06.840 --> 00:18:07.840
All right.

285
00:18:08.400 --> 00:18:09.456
I'm sorry, I've forgotten your name.

286
00:18:09.480 --> 00:18:10.920
- Whitney. Whitney Reese.
- Whitney.

287
00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:13.400
Whitney, of course.
I'm... I'm so sorry

288
00:18:13.480 --> 00:18:15.096
and unfortunately
I've left things a bit late

289
00:18:15.120 --> 00:18:16.176
and there's something
I can't get out of.

290
00:18:16.200 --> 00:18:18.120
I understand. Can I text you?

291
00:18:38.200 --> 00:18:39.360
It's perfect, Aldo.

292
00:18:42.760 --> 00:18:45.080
Oh. I was hoping we could celebrate.

293
00:18:45.160 --> 00:18:46.680
No. So was I.

294
00:18:47.360 --> 00:18:48.600
I've got a class at Juilliard.

295
00:18:48.680 --> 00:18:49.680
Oh, good.

296
00:18:49.760 --> 00:18:50.760
I promised Ben.

297
00:18:51.640 --> 00:18:54.400
I'm sure you'll have a few elbowing
for an Accordion slot.

298
00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
We should open up the fellowship.

299
00:18:58.480 --> 00:19:00.600
- What, expand our numbers?
- No, our sex.

300
00:19:00.680 --> 00:19:03.760
I mean, it feels quaint
to keep things single-gender.

301
00:19:03.840 --> 00:19:05.000
We've made our point.

302
00:19:05.080 --> 00:19:06.640
And, honestly,
we've had no real trouble

303
00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:08.400
successfully placing any of them.

304
00:19:08.600 --> 00:19:09.600
Except one.

305
00:19:10.440 --> 00:19:11.440
Oh, well.

306
00:19:12.400 --> 00:19:13.520
She had issues.

307
00:19:13.880 --> 00:19:14.920
So I've heard.

308
00:19:15.880 --> 00:19:17.720
The topic comes up
in every Citibank meeting

309
00:19:17.800 --> 00:19:18.800
with her father.

310
00:19:20.200 --> 00:19:21.320
I'm sorry about that.

311
00:19:21.520 --> 00:19:22.520
It's fine.

312
00:19:22.960 --> 00:19:24.320
It's nothing I can't handle.

313
00:19:25.680 --> 00:19:29.360
So, you want to torpedo
Accordion's founding principle?

314
00:19:30.200 --> 00:19:31.560
We'd likely lose donors.

315
00:19:32.400 --> 00:19:34.000
Yeah, I suppose that's true.

316
00:19:34.400 --> 00:19:36.840
M-Maybe it's something
we revisit down the line.

317
00:19:36.920 --> 00:19:37.920
Sure.

318
00:19:38.400 --> 00:19:40.800
Now, Bryant Park's locked
for the 25th.

319
00:19:40.880 --> 00:19:42.600
Nan asked me to help fill the place

320
00:19:42.680 --> 00:19:45.880
so the Kaplan Fund is gonna buy
some radio and outdoor advertising.

321
00:19:46.640 --> 00:19:47.920
And claqueurs.

322
00:19:48.720 --> 00:19:51.080
It's too big, Eliot.
She should have booked the Strand.

323
00:19:51.400 --> 00:19:52.520
Relax.

324
00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:54.040
It'll be great.

325
00:19:55.160 --> 00:19:56.760
And it almost falls on your birthday.

326
00:19:59.320 --> 00:20:00.760
I was... I was sorry

327
00:20:00.840 --> 00:20:03.080
you weren't able to make it
to my Mahler Three in London.

328
00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:05.400
Me, too.

329
00:20:07.720 --> 00:20:08.880
Petra had a school thing.

330
00:20:09.560 --> 00:20:13.760
And I promised Sharon I'd be there.

331
00:20:14.800 --> 00:20:15.800
Of course.

332
00:20:17.120 --> 00:20:19.320
I was just hoping
for your honest opinion.

333
00:20:20.280 --> 00:20:22.200
My player rating sheets
were off the charts.

334
00:20:23.080 --> 00:20:24.600
Those are confidential, Eliot.

335
00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:26.640
Well, the principal oboist
is a big fan.

336
00:20:28.120 --> 00:20:31.320
On the way back, I was listening
to yours with the Israeli Phil

337
00:20:31.400 --> 00:20:33.096
and I was struck
by what you managed to pull

338
00:20:33.120 --> 00:20:34.880
from the strings
in the last movement.

339
00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:38.200
I mean, how did you get them there?

340
00:20:39.040 --> 00:20:40.040
Was it the hall?

341
00:20:40.120 --> 00:20:41.360
Was it the players?

342
00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.480
The players weren't very obliging.

343
00:20:44.760 --> 00:20:47.600
The principal violinist came up to me
after the first rehearsal

344
00:20:47.680 --> 00:20:49.800
- and asked if I was a Jew.
- What?

345
00:20:49.880 --> 00:20:51.840
It seemed to him unusual,
if not suspicious

346
00:20:51.920 --> 00:20:55.680
that a non-Jew would be interested
in conducting Jewish music.

347
00:20:56.640 --> 00:20:57.920
Felt like Max Bruch.

348
00:20:58.320 --> 00:21:00.120
Well, big Jew that I am

349
00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:02.000
the Kaplan Fund has

350
00:21:02.080 --> 00:21:04.720
committed a sizable amount to them
for a klezmer commission.

351
00:21:05.920 --> 00:21:07.256
Maybe they'll invite me
to guest conduct.

352
00:21:07.280 --> 00:21:08.800
Oh, well, they'd be lucky
to have you.

353
00:21:09.200 --> 00:21:10.400
Oh, please.

354
00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:12.200
I know my place.

355
00:21:13.120 --> 00:21:15.000
Money can't always
buy you everything.

356
00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:18.000
You don't really believe that.

357
00:21:18.880 --> 00:21:20.800
I'll have you know
I tried to bribe Francesca

358
00:21:20.880 --> 00:21:22.160
to let me look at your notation.

359
00:21:22.240 --> 00:21:23.360
She sent me packing.

360
00:21:24.120 --> 00:21:25.120
Good girl.

361
00:21:25.880 --> 00:21:27.696
That gentleman sitting
over there with the gnome

362
00:21:27.720 --> 00:21:30.000
is urgently focused on our table.

363
00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:33.080
At first, I thought
he was looking at me

364
00:21:33.200 --> 00:21:35.000
but I think he's got his eye on you.

365
00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:36.880
Please try and ignore him.

366
00:21:37.360 --> 00:21:39.600
I can excuse myself
and go wash my hands

367
00:21:39.680 --> 00:21:40.840
if you'd like to be alone.

368
00:21:40.920 --> 00:21:42.360
And I would never forgive you.

369
00:21:43.960 --> 00:21:45.920
The last thing I need
is to be buttonholed in here

370
00:21:46.000 --> 00:21:47.560
by someone exactly like me.

371
00:21:49.360 --> 00:21:50.760
What time are you leaving tomorrow?

372
00:21:52.080 --> 00:21:53.760
Francesca's looking into flights.

373
00:21:54.320 --> 00:21:55.400
Well, call her off.

374
00:21:55.720 --> 00:21:56.760
Leave when you like.

375
00:21:57.800 --> 00:21:58.840
You don't have to do that.

376
00:21:59.360 --> 00:22:01.800
My motives are not
entirely altruistic.

377
00:22:02.640 --> 00:22:05.200
Just one peek. One peek
at your performing score.

378
00:22:07.960 --> 00:22:08.960
Fine.

379
00:22:09.320 --> 00:22:11.720
Would 5:15 be okay?

380
00:22:11.800 --> 00:22:13.240
- Sure.
- Okay, I mean, I do...

381
00:22:13.320 --> 00:22:14.800
I have to get turned around fast.

382
00:22:15.320 --> 00:22:16.920
We're filling a vacant position.

383
00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:19.120
Oh, please tell me it's Sebastian.

384
00:22:19.480 --> 00:22:22.680
Now, be fair, Eliot.
Sebastian has decent technique.

385
00:22:23.040 --> 00:22:24.120
He has baton.

386
00:22:24.480 --> 00:22:26.000
A month ago, I dropped into Bunkamura

387
00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:28.400
to watch the touring machine
trot out Chopin 1.

388
00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:32.160
Ol' Sebastian really is
Mr. Tempo Rubato.

389
00:22:32.520 --> 00:22:34.120
Robot-o is more like it.

390
00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:35.200
Why do you keep him on?

391
00:22:35.280 --> 00:22:37.400
Oh, he's Andris's man, you know that.

392
00:22:37.480 --> 00:22:39.080
Exactly. You inherited that decision.

393
00:22:39.160 --> 00:22:41.216
Seven years is a long time
to pretend you respect it.

394
00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:43.240
They have different
labor contracts over there.

395
00:22:45.920 --> 00:22:48.120
He's a... he's a strange guy.

396
00:22:48.600 --> 00:22:49.680
Who? Andris?

397
00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:51.120
No, Sebastian.

398
00:22:51.440 --> 00:22:53.840
He has... fetishes.

399
00:22:54.480 --> 00:22:55.680
Fetishes? Like what?

400
00:22:56.360 --> 00:22:59.000
Nostalgia for pre-war
Kalmus miniature scores

401
00:22:59.080 --> 00:23:03.480
dead-stock pencils he's seen
von Karajan hold in photographs.

402
00:23:03.560 --> 00:23:05.120
You know, that sort of thing.

403
00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:07.400
That's just sad.

404
00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:13.160
Yeah, but you're not wrong.

405
00:23:14.360 --> 00:23:16.480
I am gonna have to rotate him
at some point.

406
00:23:19.320 --> 00:23:20.320
For who?

407
00:23:25.760 --> 00:23:27.000
<i>What Love Teaches Me.</i>

408
00:23:27.560 --> 00:23:28.760
That string notation.

409
00:23:30.480 --> 00:23:32.200
Mahler gives it to you himself.

410
00:23:35.200 --> 00:23:36.320
{\an5}- Come on.
- Trust me.

411
00:23:36.400 --> 00:23:37.720
You do not want to go to school

412
00:23:37.800 --> 00:23:39.520
on someone else's
red and blue pencil.

413
00:23:40.320 --> 00:23:41.360
Least of all, mine.

414
00:23:41.760 --> 00:23:42.880
Oh, but I do.

415
00:23:42.960 --> 00:23:44.440
All right.
Will you quit pestering me?

416
00:23:44.480 --> 00:23:45.480
Yes.

417
00:23:47.040 --> 00:23:48.120
Free bowing.

418
00:23:50.160 --> 00:23:52.560
It's not pretty
for an audience to look at

419
00:23:52.640 --> 00:23:55.120
but if you can manage to keep
your players out of the weeds...

420
00:23:56.680 --> 00:23:58.040
the sound's ferocious.

421
00:24:05.080 --> 00:24:07.680
There's no glory for a robot, Eliot.

422
00:24:11.960 --> 00:24:13.120
Do your own thing.

423
00:24:35.280 --> 00:24:36.320
All right...

424
00:24:37.600 --> 00:24:40.040
Let's... stop here.

425
00:24:40.120 --> 00:24:41.920
- Thank you, Max. Very good.
- Thanks.

426
00:24:43.040 --> 00:24:45.880
Just for my own edification...

427
00:24:46.760 --> 00:24:48.680
why did you come to Juilliard?

428
00:24:51.920 --> 00:24:54.120
It's the best music conservatory
in the country?

429
00:24:54.320 --> 00:24:56.800
People from Curtis, Eastman,
and others may beg to differ.

430
00:24:57.080 --> 00:24:59.200
I mean, Juilliard's a brand, right?

431
00:24:59.280 --> 00:25:02.320
So, did you come to study
with a brand?

432
00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:03.480
- No.
- No, right.

433
00:25:03.560 --> 00:25:05.880
So there's a teacher or graduate
somewhere down the line

434
00:25:05.960 --> 00:25:08.056
who, you know, conjured
something in your imagination.

435
00:25:08.080 --> 00:25:09.800
Someone you aspire to be yourself.

436
00:25:10.840 --> 00:25:11.960
So, who was that?

437
00:25:12.040 --> 00:25:13.080
Sarah Chang.

438
00:25:14.000 --> 00:25:15.120
So you're a violinist?

439
00:25:15.200 --> 00:25:16.800
- Yeah.
- All right, okay.

440
00:25:16.880 --> 00:25:21.160
Well, I can see why you would choose
to conduct a piece like this.

441
00:25:21.240 --> 00:25:23.880
Must be a familiar pleasure
in presiding over

442
00:25:23.960 --> 00:25:26.200
a bed of strings that behave
as if they're tuning.

443
00:25:26.840 --> 00:25:27.840
Now...

444
00:25:28.120 --> 00:25:31.880
this piece is very au courant.

445
00:25:32.280 --> 00:25:35.080
I mean, here, the composer tells us

446
00:25:35.160 --> 00:25:37.960
to begin with "back-and-forth
tremolo strokes with wire brush

447
00:25:38.040 --> 00:25:40.400
and slowly sliding
crotales over skin."

448
00:25:40.800 --> 00:25:43.400
Sounds like René Redzepi's
recipe for reindeer.

449
00:25:44.880 --> 00:25:47.280
It's exciting to play
new music, isn't it?

450
00:25:47.360 --> 00:25:48.360
- Yeah.
- Yeah.

451
00:25:48.760 --> 00:25:51.880
Great. All right, please,
join the other fellows.

452
00:25:53.560 --> 00:25:57.880
Now, I know you're all
conducting students of Mr. Wolfe's

453
00:25:57.960 --> 00:26:01.720
but how many of you
are also studying composition?

454
00:26:02.600 --> 00:26:03.760
Right, what's your name?

455
00:26:03.840 --> 00:26:04.880
Olive Kerr.

456
00:26:05.680 --> 00:26:06.720
All right, Olive.

457
00:26:08.120 --> 00:26:10.240
What do you make of
what we've just been listening to?

458
00:26:10.280 --> 00:26:11.920
It's pretty awesome.

459
00:26:12.240 --> 00:26:15.000
I mean, there's
incredible atonal tension.

460
00:26:15.080 --> 00:26:17.320
I agree about the tension part.

461
00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:21.280
Now, you can intellectually
contemplate, or masturbate

462
00:26:21.360 --> 00:26:24.800
about the felicity
of the so-called "atonal"

463
00:26:24.880 --> 00:26:30.280
but the important question here
is: What are you conducting?

464
00:26:30.480 --> 00:26:34.520
What is the effect?
What is it actually doing to me?

465
00:26:34.880 --> 00:26:38.040
Good music can be
as ornate as a cathedral

466
00:26:38.120 --> 00:26:40.120
or bare as a potting shed

467
00:26:40.200 --> 00:26:43.600
so long as it allows you
to answer both those questions.

468
00:26:43.920 --> 00:26:44.920
Max.

469
00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:47.320
Come on, what do you think?

470
00:26:51.200 --> 00:26:55.400
When... Anna Thorvaldsdóttir
gave her master class

471
00:26:55.840 --> 00:26:58.200
she said she was often
influenced by the form

472
00:26:59.400 --> 00:27:03.800
and structure of landscapes
and nature she grew up within.

473
00:27:04.960 --> 00:27:06.840
But I'm not sure
she was interested per se

474
00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:09.960
in describing those actual sounds.

475
00:27:10.160 --> 00:27:11.880
Very Punkt Kontra Punkt.

476
00:27:13.840 --> 00:27:14.840
Yes.

477
00:27:15.080 --> 00:27:20.120
The intent of her composition
is vague, to say the least.

478
00:27:20.200 --> 00:27:22.960
So, if her intent is vague

479
00:27:23.040 --> 00:27:27.400
how do you, as a conductor,
have a point of view about anything?

480
00:27:28.120 --> 00:27:29.520
Now, to be fair, I mean

481
00:27:29.600 --> 00:27:31.840
there are times when you will
simply have no choice.

482
00:27:32.080 --> 00:27:34.440
And you will be made
to stand in front of an orchestra

483
00:27:34.520 --> 00:27:37.600
and pretend that there are
these invisible structures.

484
00:27:37.680 --> 00:27:40.240
But my prayer for you

485
00:27:40.600 --> 00:27:42.800
is that you will be spared
the embarrassment

486
00:27:42.880 --> 00:27:44.880
of standing on the podium
with a 4'33"

487
00:27:44.960 --> 00:27:47.200
trying to sell a car
without an engine.

488
00:27:47.440 --> 00:27:52.720
Because now, my friends,
now is the time to conduct music

489
00:27:52.800 --> 00:27:55.520
that actually requires
something of you.

490
00:27:55.840 --> 00:27:57.480
You know, music that everybody knows

491
00:27:57.560 --> 00:28:01.320
but will hear differently
when you interpret it for them.

492
00:28:02.240 --> 00:28:05.320
For instance, Max, why not a Kyrie?

493
00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:09.520
You know, like, something
like Bach's Mass in B minor.

494
00:28:11.920 --> 00:28:13.320
I'm not really into Bach.

495
00:28:14.200 --> 00:28:15.760
You're not into Bach?

496
00:28:16.600 --> 00:28:17.760
Oh, Max.

497
00:28:19.360 --> 00:28:21.360
Have you read the Schweitzer book?

498
00:28:21.440 --> 00:28:22.440
No.

499
00:28:23.080 --> 00:28:24.200
Well, you should.

500
00:28:24.600 --> 00:28:26.120
It's an important text.

501
00:28:27.000 --> 00:28:28.880
Now, Antonia Brico thought so.

502
00:28:29.200 --> 00:28:31.960
So much so that she shipped
herself to Equatorial Africa

503
00:28:32.040 --> 00:28:34.720
and canoed up the Congo River
to track Schweitzer down

504
00:28:34.800 --> 00:28:37.520
and ask him to teach her
what he knew about Bach.

505
00:28:38.040 --> 00:28:39.976
I mean, somewhere,
I've got a picture of her in a...

506
00:28:40.000 --> 00:28:41.520
in a pith helmet.

507
00:28:41.600 --> 00:28:42.600
I mean, have you...

508
